I have a confession to make. Until last month, I had never been glamping. I know, I know. It is embarrassing to admit especially given the province I am so proud to call my chosen home is famed for its glamping excursions. Ontarians and West Coasters and Americans and Brits and Europeans flock to rural New Brunswick to experience our world-renowned glamping resorts.

But finally, last month, after the busiest few months of my life, I took a weekend to relax and reconnect with my family at Tides & Timber in Charlotte County, New Brunswick. 
 
I was blown away. Obviously the location helps. Tides & Timber and its four domes are majestically situated where New Brunswick nature meets the Bay of Fundy's world famous tides, offering the ultimate East Coast glamping experience and sure enough, we delighted in everything they had to offer. My wife, sons and I went canoeing and kayaking and in doing so discovered a truly stunning hidden waterfall. We made s’mores on the fire, we walked our dog on the trails and explored the woods, we ran, we read (I devoured Ann-Marie MacDonald’s Canadian literary masterpiece Fall On Your Knees in two days sitting in the hot tub) and crucially, we relaxed and connected in a uniquely special way….

To read more visit the @themaritimeedit website or copy this link: https://bit.ly/edition59.

In short, go and visit Isabel, Ryan and Myles at @tidesandtimberglamping. It was one of the best weekends of my 2022. Certainly the most relaxed. And be sure to book now. They reopen on March 24th for the 2023 season and 2023 and 2024 are unsurprisingly booking up fast.

One Sunday afternoon in a tiny postage-stamp garden, James Mullinger made the life-altering decision to give it all up: the London pubs, bustling city streets, and a flourishing comedy career. But where in the world would he and his partner raise a family? The English countryside? Toronto? New York?
Hmmm. How about St. John … sorry, Saint John, New Brunswick?
Brit Happens chronicles Mullinger’s lifetime of adventures, from his beginnings as a shy and nervous kid collecting comedy records at the neighborhood video store, to rising through the ranks of GQ magazine and meeting his personal idols Jerry Seinfeld and Paul McCartney, to imagining the possibility of another life in Canada. From the highs and lows of London to beginning anew in New Brunswick, Brit Happens tells gut-busting stories of success and failure and the unpredictable grind of stand-up comedy. It also offers a laugh-out-loud look at life in Atlantic Canada from the region’s funniest outsider-turned-local.

Outtake! This was the frame before what became the cover of my memoir Brit Happens - Living The Canadian Dream. Sean McGrath and I were on a windy Gondola Point Beach with the ferry boat behind me and the wind was blowing dramatically. This meant it was very hard to keep my fringe (or, ahem, quiff) out of my eyes. A second after I scooped it back, Sean captured the cover shot that @goose_lane and their experts across the country said should be the cover shot. I’m immensely grateful to Goose Lane for everything and to all of you who have kindly read it. It’s been a joy to receive so many messages over Christmas from people who found it under their tree and have enjoyed it these past few days. If you have time, please do leave a review on Amazon, it is spectacularly helpful for small, first time authors like myself. Thank you!

Personal 2022 highlight: The KV Hurricanes making the finals of the Lancaster tournament last month. Proudest ever hockey dad moment from a dad who is still struggling to stay standing up on skates. But my own struggles on the ice only make me respect and admire everyone who plays hockey - in any capacity - even more. And sincere thanks to the amazing coaches in this province and across the country supporting our kids and guiding them in this beautiful sport.

The first warm up show is the scariest. 13 pages of scraps and notes of untested jokes and half formed ideas. But last night at @longbaybrewery was an utter joy thanks to all the lovely people who packed the place out despite it clashing with rather a big hockey game. 60 minutes of brand new jokes written over the past few weeks plus 30 minutes of bits that started life in this same room a year ago only to become fully formed tour show routines. It was the funnest 90 mins I’ve had in ages, and we all made it home in time to watch Canada win the final. Happy days! What a great way to start the show building process. Next week’s show is sold out but we will be adding more dates shortly. Thank you all so much!

Few things make me happier than working on a @paniniukofficial @paniniamerica sticker album. I have been collecting them since 1986 (I was 8 years old and I bought a packet a week with my pocket money and would swap doubles with friends in the playground. “Got, got, got, need, NEED!” They still give me as much joy now as they did them, especially as I now get to do them with my children. My mum found this @strangerthingstv beauty in the UK and bought it for Hunter for Christmas (River got an equally awesome @minecraft @paniniukofficial sticker album). A visual love letter to cinema, Empire Of Light @empirelightfilm had a profound effect on me. An absolutely stunning film (as you would expect from Roger Deakins) starring Michael Ward and Olivia Colman about cinema, mental illness, racism, growing up in England in the eighties, youth, middle age and so much more. Sam Mendes’ most personal film (and first as screenwriter) and it is unbearably moving and utterly beautiful in equal measure. For two hours I was transported back in time to my formative years watching movies such as Stir Crazy, Being There, Chariots Of Fire and The Blues Brothers.

@jamesmullinger is an award-winning writer, comedian, and filmmaker. In April 2016 and 2018, James sold out Harbour Station Arena in Saint John with his uniquely hilarious stand-up show, outselling Jerry Seinfeld, Jeff Dunham and Guns N' Roses when they played the same venue. An award-winning CBC documentary about the show titled City On Fire was aired nationally to rave reviews. His latest stand-up special, Almost Canadian, shot straight to #1 on the iTunes charts.
 
In June 2017 he launched Atlantic Canada's first-ever international magazine, [EDIT] — an award-winning premium media brand devoted to celebrating business leaders and creatives doing the unexpected while expanding Canada’s global reach. James is also the host of the hit #1 TV series, Atlantic Edition, that sees him interviewing icons on the east coast. His podcast Mullinger Meets Canadians reached the Top 30 podcast charts and his memoir Brit Happens - Living The Canadian Dream was published by Goose Lane Editions in May 2022 to rave reviews.

Such an incredible honour to be asked to deliver the keynote speech on Saturday morning at one of my favourite places (@saintjohnfpl) for @writersfednb WordSpring Book Festival. The highlight was making the most dear friends in a single day that I have ever made. As well as catching up with others who I befriended last year. And that I got to meet so many writers that I have admired from afar as a fan. Oh and best of all, my son Hunter worked my book stall and got to see me do stand up, deliver a keynote about my childhood working on my dad’s book stall travelling the UK’s book fairs and learned why I love libraries, librarians and school teachers so much and why I’ve always insisted he hold a book in his hand for at least an hour a day. Thank you Rhonda and Kris and everyone at the Writers’ Federation of New Brunswick. I am genuinely in awe of what you made happen this week.

I live for playing venues like this and this Saturday is going to be a dream!

I know I have written and talked at length about my love of playing community halls, churches and local arts centres. Sure I love big theatres, packed comedy clubs and the occasional arena but I live for the atmosphere of a small hall. So I could not be more excited to be performing at the legendary Harvey Hall this Saturday! 

This historic hall - and lifeblood of the creative arts community - was built in 1884. It had been tragically derelict for six years before a heroic team of local volunteers worked tirelessly to bring it back to its former glory. And now it’s back in a big way! 

I will be there at 7pm on Saturday 17th June with my new show plus I will be debuting some upcoming material for CBC’s The Debaters, exclusively that night! Book tickets now, seating is very limited.

Synopsis: 

The Harvey Hall is delighted to share James Mullinger’s tenth year living in New Brunswick and he’s coming to present a very special show to celebrate! 

After publishing his bestselling memoir 𝘉𝘳𝘪𝘵 𝘏𝘢𝘱𝘱𝘦𝘯𝘴-𝘓𝘪𝘷𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘊𝘢𝘯𝘢𝘥𝘪𝘢𝘯 𝘋𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘮, creating his own magazine celebrating Atlantic Canada, and creating and starring in New Brunswick’s 𝘧𝘪𝘳𝘴𝘵 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳 sitcom, he is coming to the Harvey Hall stage with a full length stand up show sharing what he has learned about this special place over the past decade. Irreverent, honest, unpredictable but always hilarious, James is a Canadian citizen now and the gloves are off!

Share this ten year celebration with us on Saturday, June 17th!  Doors open at 6:30 for a 7:00 show and you’ll need advance tickets for what we expect to be a sold out show!

Like most people I rented Raiders and Temple of Doom numerous times on VHS in the mid-eighties. Back when many of us had to rent the actual VHS player too! Then in 1989, aged 11, I couldn’t believe my luck when I won tickets to see Last Crusade at a special advance press screening in a competition in the Radio Times. My dad and I took the train up to London and it was without doubt the most exciting and glamourous moment of my life thus far. I couldn’t believe they handed out beautiful press brochures that were gold dust to movie fans like us and after the movie my dad and I collected all the discarded ones from the floor to sell at conventions. I knew there and then I wanted to work in magazines so I could do this again. Sure enough, a decade later my magazine career began and in 2008 I went to see Crystal Skull with @bypaulwilson and after the movie I did what I always did: collected up all the brochures from the floor. Pictured here are all the original brochures and tickets and even my original Crusade VHS which has been worn down I watched it so often. So last night when I took my own sons to see the latest Indy film - Dial of Destiny - it was a dream come true. Alas no brochures to pick up and we missed the end due to a fire alarm going off after some burned popcorn (yes, seriously!) but it was still magical and wonderful and, above all, memorable!

When I was 11 years old in 1988, my best friend Julian Tuddenham introduced me to what I didn’t know would become two of the great loves of my life - Guns N Roses and horror movies. Our dream was to see Gun N Roses live (and watch A Nightmare On Elm Street, a dream that my cousin Lucy Powis made true) and I begged my parents for tickets to see GNR at the Monsters Of Rock festival for my 12th birthday. When they handed me an envelope on my birthday I was overjoyed until they said it was “the next best thing to Guns N Roses live”. It was tickets to see The Shadows at the Reading Hexagon. This is clearly not the next best thing, but when I heard the first twang of Hank Marvin’s guitar live in that glorious theatre space tears rolled down my cheek in sheer emotional joy at the unreal and uplifting life changing experience of live entertainment. I knew there and then that this was a feeling I wanted to feel my entire life. It was something out of this world. 34 years then went by. I had two beautiful children in that time and Julian remains a best friend today. Five weeks ago he saw GNR at Glastonbury and called me saying it was worth the wait. Then last night I got to experience the band live myself in my chosen home of New Brunswick and with my oldest son who is now 12. He got what I didn’t get to experience back in 1989 last night when, miraculously and somewhat inexplicably, the greatest rock n roll band of all time (in my opinion) chose to open their epic North American tour in the Paradise City of Moncton, New Brunswick. The 3-hour show was as blisteringly epic as we had dreamed it would be and it was a joy to see my heroes love this place I am so proud to call my home. I can’t describe the feeling when Axl bounded onto the stage screaming: “Hello Moncton!” Thank you GNR for putting NB on the map. And thank you anyone involved in accomplishing such a slick and professional event that we will be seeing many more game changing legends looking to perform here. Swipe through these photos to see the ticket for my first ever live concert gig in 1990 and my son’s first in 2023. #GNRNB #gunsnroses #gnr #gnrmoncton @evenko @livenationcanada @livenation @livenationfans

Next year will mark my 20th anniversary as a stand up comedian. To celebrate this milestone, I am very excited to say that I will be embarking on a tour across Canada (plus some dates in the States and the UK) featuring 100 minutes of the very best material from my 20 year career.

That’s right, I am quite ridiculously doing a “greatest hits” tour! And as utterly stupid as that sounds, I am essentially looking back over the dozens of hours of material I have performed to an estimated 350,000 people in the past 20 years and I will be crafting a 100-minute show of the very best received jokes, interspersed with new, untold stories from the road. A retrospective show filled with jokes you may know and love, jokes I haven’t performed in Canada before and new stories about the crazy things that happen in this job.

Tour dates will all be announced in coming months but I can reveal that my big hometown show and only Saint John date of 2024 will be at the Imperial Theatre @imperialtheatre on Saturday 27 April 2024. Save the date and tickets will go on sale early next month!

I’m very excited about this and for those of you that enjoy the small, intimate work-in-progress shows, I am delighted to share that I will still be doing warm up shows at Long Bay in which I will test the old jokes to see which still make the cut! 

To still be doing this job that I dreamed of as a child, but - because of crippling nerves, shyness and anxiety - never thought I would get to do is something I still can’t quite believe and never stop appreciating. Looking forward to celebrating with you all!

In 1914, Hudson’s Bay opened a Trading Post at Ward Inlet, Nunavut - about 40 miles from Iqaluet. In 1949, Hudson’s Bay moved their operations to this beautiful Apex Beach location to take advantage of the action happening at the nearby US air force base (where they were keeping an eye on the Russians amongst other activities). The beautiful close knit community of Apex was created as a result of this. I first saw Ice Cube @icecube live at the Reading Festival in 1994 - swipe to see the amazing line up that day. Publisher's summary

Winner, New Brunswick Book Award (Non-Fiction)

One Sunday afternoon in a tiny postage-stamp garden, James Mullinger made the life-altering decision to give it all up: the London pubs, bustling city streets, and a flourishing comedy career. But where in the world would he and his partner raise a family? The English countryside? Toronto? New York?

Hmmm. How about St. John … sorry, Saint John, New Brunswick?

Brit Happens chronicles Mullinger’s lifetime of adventures, from his beginnings as a shy and nervous kid collecting comedy records at the neighborhood video store, to rising through the ranks of GQ magazine and meeting his personal idols Jerry Seinfeld and Paul McCartney, to imagining the possibility of another life in Canada. From the highs and lows of London to beginning anew in New Brunswick, Brit Happens tells gut-busting stories of success and failure and the unpredictable grind of stand-up comedy. It also offers a laugh-out-loud look at life in Atlantic Canada from the region’s funniest outsider-turned-local.

Just had the immense pleasure of watching one of the very best stand up specials I have seen this year. Kevin Bridges @kevinbridgescomedian is a huge star in the UK and his releases are always great, but this brand new one (released on DVD this month) is so intelligent, profound, touching and thoughtful that I was compelled to watch the whole thing again immediately. Mental health, social media addiction, anxiety, COVID, insomnia, anal health, marriage, fatherhood and so much more, this show is far reaching and, above all, hilariously funny. I laughed like a drain, cried at the denouement and vowed to follow Kevin’s lead in life and work and mental health. And kudos to anyone that releases their new specials on physical media. Makes me very happy to own the real thing.

What a ridiculously enjoyable year of shows! And what a way to celebrate 10 years of living in Canada. Thank you to everyone who came out to see me in theatres, clubs, arenas, domes, sheds, fields, bars, churches, breweries, arts ventures, opera houses and amphitheatres in 2023. In almost two decades of doing comedy, this has been by far the most fun I have ever had on stage. From workshopping this new show with intimate gigs this time last year, to touring it across Canada including the Great Arctic North, it has been a uniquely fulfilling experience creating dozens of new stories for this year’s show and my new book that (I hope) will be published by Christmas. Oh and also premiering New Brunswick’s first ever sitcom on television nationally and on the big screen in the midst of all this. I can’t thank you all enough for your kindness, friendship, support and laughter. I’m back on the road next week and tickets are on sale for tour dates in Toronto, Pictou, Summerside, Fredericton, Digby and Saint John. British Columbia dates going on sale later this month. Had such a wonderful time at @oceanstoneseasideresort researching and writing the cover story for the latest volume of @themaritimeedit and interviewing visionary Dean Leland @etlca for this exclusive Edit Media film with @tylannosaurus and @jroberts.co. 

Oceanstone Resort @oceanstoneseasideresort in Indian Harbour, Nova Scotia, is a truly magical slice of seaside heaven, minutes from what is unquestionably Atlantic Canada’s top tourist destination, Peggy’s Cove. But fear not, Oceanstone is all about wellness, detachment, serenity and relaxation and, despite the close proximity, feels a long way from the crowds and tour buses that fill the iconic cove almost each and every day. Oceanstone has been a holiday staple for many families, couples and individuals for decades. A preferred spot for
weddings and corporate retreats too, it has always been known for its stunning shoreline, cozy rustic cottages and uniquely Maritime hospitality.

But since entrepreneur and former corporate executive
Dean Leland took over, this sumptuous spot has been elevated to a truly world-class destination. And in the past six months, Leland has added a hydrothermal spa experience to match the very best in the world. As he tells [EDIT]’s @jamesmullinger “the smell of seaweed and wood smoke, the clear sound of ocean waves, the tender touch of sea mist and the magical shoreline all make Oceanstone a special healing place,” so it made perfect sense to add a hydrothermal spa.

The addition of the hydrothermal spa is a game changer not only for the resort but for the region as a whole. I visited Dean Leland @etlca at the resort to learn more for this exclusive film by @jroberts.co. 

Interview filmed by Tyler Warren Ellis @tylannosaurus @this_celluloid_dream.
